{"_id":"3nVIvE45aMEtr64j","name":"06 - The Planet Algol","content":"<div class=\"coriolis-community-atlas-journal-entry\">\n<h1>THE PLANET ALGOL</h1>\n<p>The planet Algol is the hub of the system and where the major population centers are located. Most people, city dwellers and rebels alike, live in the planet’s two temperate bands. The planet’s habitable zones are crowded by cities both old and new – including Yasul, Akhandar-O-Sharif, Belem, and Yousfana. These are surrounded by widespread wastelands. Colonies and mining operations exist across the entire planet and are common throughout the system – including on moons and asteroids, and in the Cloud Belt.</p>\n<h2>THE TANZIM HIGHLANDS</h2>\n<p>North of the arid Mengol Sea, a volcanic massif spreads out. For the most part, this is an inhospitable plateau: In some places, the mountains of this range rise above the atmosphere. As such, the plateau would work well as a bridge to orbit – a natural beanstalk to the skies. So when the Consortium and the Zenithians arrived, they immediately began building a cable car system from Akhandar to the top of what is known as the Rhaas-Tanzim.</p>\n<p>The system was ready in record time but Yihanna and the rebels who were based in the mountains immediately began a campaign of sabotage, making the cable car impossible to use. The old space port on Rhaas-Tanzim is now a deserted town visited only by looters and reconnaissance drones from the Legion cruiser Gevennon-Parras. The massif is now partly rebel-controlled, and is rumored to be home to Slavers’ headquarters and opor farms.</p>\n<h3>✺ “SUBSTANCE O”</h3>\n<p>The opor cartel Yar-Figri has long controlled the fields used to grow opor poppy and black hellebore on the plateaus of the Tanzim highlands. The poppies are picked by slaves or unskilled workers, then processed into opor aboard mobile refineries built in old, repurposed free traders. This is then sold in the big cities or exported across the Horizon. Algol opor goes by many names, such as \"Demon's Eye\", \"Smoke of Freedom\" and \"Bright Star\".</p>\n<p>Recently, a new type of opor has also begun to spread, notably in the entertainment districts of AYM. This highly addictive variant is known as “Substance O”, as users often express an expectant “O” at the first hit. It is not known who developed the drug, but it is rumored that purges have taken place within Yar-Figri, which indicates a new player may be present.</p>\n<h2>MENGOL’S MINING ARCHIPELAGO</h2>\n<p>The saltwater Mengol Sea was once a place full of life, where fishermen lived along silvery white beaches and AkhandarO-Sharif reigned like a pearl on the southern shore. That all changed when the Consortium and the Zenithians arrived. The seabed was rich in nodules of almost pure metals, but harvesting those nodules using submarines and divers was expensive and difficult.</p>\n<p>The now-cursed engineer Yim-Ar Salbara pointed out to the Colonial Agency's akbars that mining could be facilitated by blowing up a rocky tongue separating the low-lying and arid Yafsa Desert from the sea. The sea would drain and the fishermen would be without jobs, but they could be employed as laborers in the new, open mines. With a little luck, the Yafsa Desert could also flourish.</p>\n<p>With profit in mind and dreams of an endless stream of birr, the project was launched under the name \"The Salbara Miracle\". Engineers easily blasted away the headland using strategically placed antimatter charges, which the Colonial Agency acquired under suspicious circumstances. In a month or so, all the water had run onto the sand: The Mengol Sea was drained and dried out quickly, while the Yafsa Desert turned into a lifeless salt marsh.</p>\n<p>Today, “salbara” is a curse word in the area, and Mengol's seabed is a parched plain dotted with mining units, dried up salt lakes, and shantytowns where the laborers who work the salt and mining operations live in misery. The shantytowns are a breeding ground for rebels, and attacks on mining drones, gigantic excavators, and the outskirts of AYM itself are now part of everyday life for people living on the seabed.</p>\n<h2>THE YAFSA STEPPE</h2>\n<p>Towards the South Pole, the salt marsh Yafsa turns into a frozen wasteland. This vast steppe is frozen all year round but also rich in deposits of natural gases and precious metals. The harsh climate and inaccessibility mean that major companies have eschewed it in favor of other, more lucrative sites. But hardy, independent miners can eke out a life here. It’s a solitary existence, where one shelters in a frozen outpost or perishes in one of the many snowstorms.</p></div>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"9lJzeDMf24iRID0x":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"6UejYCugCyH1dOwV","name":"10 - Akhandar-O-Sharif","content":"<div class=\"coriolis-community-atlas-journal-entry\">\n<h1>AKHANDAR-O-SHARIF</h1>\n<p>Akhandar-O-Sharif is one of the oldest cities on the planet Algol – although it doesn’t look the part as much of the city was destroyed in the years following The Age of Flaming Tears. When Slavers blew up the Algolan Church of Sharmadom, most of the city's inhabitants fled. When the Zenithians arrived, they found mostly ruins around a dying city center and a decrepit harbor.</p>\n<p>This suited the Consortium and the other large companies just fine. Demolition and large-scale construction started immediately and today it is almost impossible to see that there was once a ruined city here. The new buildings were built directly on top of the old ones, or on platforms built above the ruins when that was more economical. Cloud towers, spires, Dabaran dome complexes, and the recentlyfinished Crater Cathedral have given the city a completely different look. Only in the poorer districts and shantytowns do ruins from the past stand out, as if pointing an accusing finger at those who would forget the past.</p>\n<p>Today, Akhandar (as it is more commonly called) has spread and merged with the other big cities on the southern shore of the Mengol Sea to form the gigantic metropolis known as AYM. This is almost comparable in size to the Conglomerate on Kua.</p>\n<h2>POLITICS, LAW AND ORDER</h2>\n<p>If there is one place in the Horizon that is governed in the same way as Coriolis and Kua, it is Akhandar. The Zenithian factions, led by the Consortium and the Zenithian Hegemony and backed by other large corporations, today support the entire Akhandar community – just as they do on the rest of Algol. This oligarchy differs in one important respect from Coriolis: There are no channels for popular representation. It is only through the benevolence of these companies that a social safety net exists.</p>\n<h3>✺ THE KHASARS</h3>\n<p>The leaders and entourages of the largest governing corporations gather once a month in the Zenith Palace, located in the city's central district of Khasa. The palace is a monumental building in the whitest marble, built by the Consortium and the Hegemony when the modern city was newly founded. Today it houses the city's central bureaucracy. Here, the war against the rebels is coordinated, decisions on the distribution of the districts are taken, and negotiations on major bribes are conducted. The district has given its name to the city's governing council, the Khasars.</p>\n<h3>✺ THE COMPANY POLICE</h3>\n<p>Order in the city is maintained by various company-controlled police forces. These go by different names depending on which district they belong to, such as the Khasa Guard, the Colonial Police and the Hyperion Granite Guards. The Consortium Guards is the largest unit and similar in organization to the Coriolis Guards. It is responsible for several districts, and provides security services to smaller companies – for a fee. Specific laws vary from district to district, as does the relationship between the police and the populace. In addition, there are laws that apply citywide – mostly related to rebel crimes, industrial espionage, and the like.</p>\n<h3>✺ THE REBEL HUNTERS</h3>\n<p>The companies have formed a collective military unit called the Rebel Hunters, and the Legion has trained its members in urban warfare. The Rebel Hunters’ job is to clear out the various rebel nests that grow like mushrooms in the shantytowns and The Undercity. It’s a mission with a high mortality rate, but compensation includes high salaries and access to the unit’s exclusive entertainment palace in the large Khorasan district. The Rebel Hunters are equipped with the very latest technology from the Consortium's arsenal – such as grav belts, combat gliders, and vomit fields.</p>\n</div>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"9lJzeDMf24iRID0x":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"9LXf6zulxlarbTvG","name":"08 - Travel on Algol","content":"<div class=\"coriolis-community-atlas-journal-entry\">\n<h1>TRAVEL ON ALGOL</h1>\n<p>Algolans only travel when they absolutely must. They prefer to stay in their cities, villages, and mining outposts. But when they do travel, there are a variety of options.</p>\n<p>In the cities that have been modernized by the corporations, there is everything from cable cars to rickshaws and privately owned grav taxis. Longer distances in the cities are covered by high-speed trains similar to those in the Conglomerate, while intra-atmospheric ships and spaceships serve the rich and powerful.</p>\n<p>In rural areas, people often travel via various crawler vehicles which often have some kind of exploration function. Caravans with wagons, grav trailers, dromedons (imported from Lubau) and elephants are also used for transport. The elephants were brought by the Firstcome colonizers and are available in every conceivable size: from the small, fast dwarf elephants that pull trucks on the outskirts of cities, to the woolly giants that the rebels train and use in the wilderness. In addition, elephants have also gone feral and large populations of wild elephants roam the warmer plains near the planet's equator.</p>\n<p>The Legion established a No Fly Zone over Haven and the entire Tanzim highlands after it became aware the rebels were smuggling weapons into the area and that they had access to spaceships with atmospheric capability. Mobile drone batteries and combat satellites deployed by GevennonParras patrol the skies to prevent flights, a situation that has irritated several corporations with operations in the area.</p></div>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"9lJzeDMf24iRID0x":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"IX274TWkhuOZa2E3","name":"07 - People and Culture","content":"<div class=\"coriolis-community-atlas-journal-entry\">\n<h1>PEOPLE AND CULTURE</h1>\n<p>The life of the Algolan people is rough. Whether they toil in the factories or in the mines and logging camps, their lot is one of hard labor. But just as the two suns Algol and Persei circle each other, the toils of the day alternate with the pleasures of the night. The big cities can compete in decadence with anything found on Coriolis or in the Cloud City on Dabaran. Entertainment districts known for their courtesan houses, as well as pit fights, grav racing, and other sporting events. Visitors can partake of countless types of kohôl, as well as opor, arrash, and a new drug, \"Substance O\".</p>\n<p>The countryside is at least as harsh on the people as life in the cities. Characterized by vast gravel deserts, empty tundra, forbidding mountain ranges and deep, dark forests, Algol seems designed to stop human progress. But this does not prevent settlers and companies from building mines or prospecting for precious metals. As the Algolan expression goes: “A miner in the morning can be a pasha by night.\" There are many who have succeeded and found great wealth. But just as many have lost fortunes to kohôl, arrash, or unfavorable contracts with the Colonial Agency.</p>\n<h2>TWIN SHADOWS</h2>\n<p>\"To be split like an Algolan\" is a phrase that has spread throughout the Third Horizon. The phrase refers to the phenomenon that all inhabitants on the planet have two shadows, cast by the system’s twin suns. This phenomenon seems to have spread to the Algolan’s way of looking at everyday life, as a dichotomy between hard work and excesses in entertainment.</p>\n<h2>THE PRAYER TOWERS</h2>\n<p>A famous architectural feature on Algol are the prayer towers which, since the time of the ancients, have been erected on the chapels and churches of the Icons. In the hands of the Zenithians, these have reached unimaginable height and splendor.</p>\n<p>In miniature format, the colorful prayer towers have become a popular prayer focus elsewhere in the Horizon, especially on Coriolis.</p>\n<p>Prayer is for the Algolans the most important of the Church of the Icons' nine sacred rites. All across the planet, society grinds to a halt as crowds gather to pray at dawn and dusk. Those who do not see prayer as important therefore usually stay inside during the early morning hours and when the evening shift begins.</p>\n<h2>DAY OF THE GOLD EATERS</h2>\n<p>A distorted Zenithian tradition that has spread from the Monolith to Algol is the Day of the Gold Eaters, when people feast on food and drink. To display their wealth and also receive the Merchant’s blessing, parts of the food are dressed in thin layers of gold leaf. Flakes of gold are also mixed in beverages. It’s believed that the more gold that is ingested, the more successful the Algolan will be.</p>\n<h2>BONFIRE NIGHT</h2>\n<p>On the last day of the Player's segment, the arrival of spring is celebrated with the bonfire, Charan, when the people light bonfires and jump over small fires. At the same time as celebrants jump over the fire, they chant the following rhyme:</p>\n<p><em>\"A great reprieve</em></p>\n<p><em>On Charan's Eve</em></p>\n<p><em>I burn my gown </em></p>\n<p><em>T</em><em>o sun retrieve\"</em></p>\n<p>The festival is celebrated with grilled lamb, dried fruit and nuts. Since the arrival of the Zenithians, the rebels have allowed the fire to gain even more significance, and arson attacks are often carried out on corporate buildings or interests during the night that follows.</p>\n<h2>MUSIC AND THEATER</h2>\n<p>The Algolan are a musical people. There are street musicians throughout the cities and in settlements across the planet. Often, they play one of the traditional wind instruments that are reminiscent of crooked and multi-pipe flutes. Before the Mengol Sea was drained, musicians also played on large shells, which today are rare and command incredible prices from collectors.</p>\n<p>Unlike the music, which tends to be happy, Algolan theater and festivals are gloomy affairs. Algolan tragedy is known all over the Horizon. Several actors, such as Omar Shiri and Amma dol-Haerric, launched their careers on Algol only to become famous throughout the Horizon via the Bulletin and the popular series, “The Plantation Owner's Daughter”. In the Khasa district of Akhandar-O-Sharif, the Mahumada Theater is considered a must-play venue for any self-respecting actor – preferably during one of the festivals in the city.</p></div>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"9lJzeDMf24iRID0x":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"OfFNw3lAjYZVDlRb","name":"C - Star System Rhaas (C)","content":"<div class=\"coriolis-community-atlas-journal-entry\">\n<p><img src=\"modules/coriolis-community-atlas/images/star_system_rhass_c.png\" width=\"550\" height=\"290\" /></p>\n<p><strong>RHAAS (C) </strong></p>\n<p>◆ <strong>GHUL</strong> – Rumored to be home to secret slaver bases</p>\n<p>◆ <strong>RHAAS-MOHRA MINING STATION</strong> – Co-owned and jointly operated by Hyperion (a Consortium member) and The Free League</p>\n<p>◆ <strong>ZABRA</strong> – The remains of the planet Zabra circle in this orbit</p>\n</div>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"9lJzeDMf24iRID0x":3},"flags":{}}
